<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="726" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[112,648,960,1143]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">
DISTRIBUTION. — Présent en 
<collectingCountry box="[400,447,960,984]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Inde</collectingCountry>
, à Java, en 
<collectingCountry box="[113,184,987,1011]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Nouvelle-Guinée</collectingCountry>
et 
<collectingCountry box="[218,413,987,1011]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Nouvelle-Calédonie</collectingCountry>
et dans de nombreuses autres îles du Pacifique où il a très probablement été involontairement introduit (
<bibRefCitation author="PERKINS R. C. L. &amp; CHEESMAN L. E." box="[383,639,1039,1063]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" refId="ref7449" refString="PERKINS R. C. L. &amp; CHEESMAN L. E. 1928. - Hymenoptera. Fasc. 1. Apoidea, Sphecoidea andVespoidea. Insects of Samoa and other Samoan terrestrial Arthropoda 3 (5). Bristish Museum (Natural History), London, 32 p." type="book" year="1928">Perkins &amp; Cheesman 1928</bibRefCitation>
; Tadauchi 1994; 
<bibRefCitation author="PAULY A. &amp; MUNZINGER J." box="[273,526,1066,1090]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" pagination="153 - 166" refId="ref7407" refString="PAULY A. &amp; MUNZINGER J. 2003. - Contribution a la connaissance des Hymenoptera Apoidea de Nouvelle- Caledonie et de leurs relations avec la flore butinee. Annales de la Societe entomologique de France 39: 153 - 166." type="journal article" year="2003">Pauly &amp; Munzinger 2003</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="CHEESMAN L. E." pageId="7" pageNumber="726" pagination="169 - 191" refId="ref6899" refString="CHEESMAN L. E. 1936. - Hymenoptera of the New Hebrides and Banks Islands. The Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London 85 (7): 169 - 191." type="journal article" year="1936">Cheesman (1936)</bibRefCitation>
le signale des îles Malekula, Banks et Vanua Lava au 
<collectingCountry box="[141,227,1119,1143]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[112,649,1166,1349]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">
DIAGNOSE. — Brun noir; clypeus, mesonotum et face externe des tibias postérieurs coriacés; face à pubescence grise; des franges de soies jaune pâle sur les joues et le bord antérieur du clypeus; ailes hyalines, abdomen lisse et brillant; sternites gastraux bordés d’une étroite bande de soies blanches; soies de la scopa longues et noires. 
<quantity box="[186,261,1325,1349]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" unit="mm" value="14.0">14 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="726" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[111,648,1389,1700]" box="[113,233,1389,1415]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">REMARQUE</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[111,648,1389,1700]" lastBlockId="7.[677,1210,216,275]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">
Les espèces de ce genre butinent de préférence les 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" box="[114,284,1451,1478]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Convolvulaceae</taxonomicName>
du genre 
<taxonomicName box="[397,484,1452,1477]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[397,484,1452,1477]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Ipomoea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, en particulier 
<taxonomicName box="[115,313,1484,1509]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pes-caprae">
<emphasis box="[115,313,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Ipomoea pes-caprae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
que l’on retrouve sur toutes les plages pantropicales (
<bibRefCitation author="PAULY A. &amp; MUNZINGER J." box="[345,634,1515,1542]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" pagination="153 - 166" refId="ref7407" refString="PAULY A. &amp; MUNZINGER J. 2003. - Contribution a la connaissance des Hymenoptera Apoidea de Nouvelle- Caledonie et de leurs relations avec la flore butinee. Annales de la Societe entomologique de France 39: 153 - 166." type="journal article" year="2003">Pauly &amp; Munzinger 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Comme l’ont observé 
<bibRefCitation author="PAULY A. &amp; MUNZINGER J." box="[340,619,1546,1573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" pagination="153 - 166" refId="ref7407" refString="PAULY A. &amp; MUNZINGER J. 2003. - Contribution a la connaissance des Hymenoptera Apoidea de Nouvelle- Caledonie et de leurs relations avec la flore butinee. Annales de la Societe entomologique de France 39: 153 - 166." type="journal article" year="2003">Pauly &amp; Munzinger (2003)</bibRefCitation>
en 
<collectingCountry box="[111,328,1578,1605]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Nouvelle-Calédonie</collectingCountry>
, les quatre spécimens collectés par Risbec au 
<collectingCountry box="[264,355,1610,1637]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
sont parasités par l’acarien 
<taxonomicName authority="(Trouessart, 1904)" baseAuthorityName="Trouessart" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[114,551,1641,1668]" class="Arachnida" family="Chaetodactylidae" genus="Chaetodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ludwigi">
<emphasis box="[114,349,1641,1667]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Chaetodactylus ludwigi</emphasis>
(Trouessart, 1904)
</taxonomicName>
. Cet acarien décrit des 
<collectingCountry box="[260,398,1673,1700]" name="Micronesia" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">îles Carolines</collectingCountry>
, parasite spécifiquement les espèces du genre 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berthold" authorityYear="1827" box="[894,993,216,242]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Lithurgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[894,993,216,242]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Lithurgus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
depuis 
<collectingCountry box="[1077,1205,216,243]" name="Madagascar" pageId="7" pageNumber="726">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, l’Inde, Java, jusqu’à Tahiti (
<bibRefCitation author="FAIN A. &amp; PAULY A." box="[969,1181,248,275]" pageId="7" pageNumber="726" pagination="125 - 142" refId="ref7080" refString="FAIN A. &amp; PAULY A. 2001. - Notes on phoretic deutonymphs of mites (Acari) associated with Old World Megachilidae and Anthophoridae (Insecta Hymenoptera), mainly from Madagascar. 1. Families Chaetodactylidae, Acaridae, Histiostomatidae and Winterschmidtiidae (Astigmata). Belgian Journal of Entomology 3: 125 - 142." type="journal article" year="2001">Fain &amp; Pauly 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
